segments.text: had a horse and buggy, but somebody would invite us to ride.
And the way I, that's how I learned to swim was the coach, the swim coach taught me, you know, on these picnics.
And did the whole faculty go to the picnic?
Well, whoever, you know, wanted to.
It was just the social ones and, you know.
What kind of food would be served?
Oh, you'd bring your, have to bring your
All your food.
What was, at your house, what were your favorite things that y'all ate?
Fried chicken.
I can't think, but we ate well.
What kind of cooking stove did your mother have?
What did she cook on?
Well, she cooked on a gas stove.
And Mama didn't do much cooking.
We always had a cook.

Mama didn't do much cooking, but we always, I mean, had people living with us that paid us, I mean, I'm sure helped with the salary, but when the school crossed the street, when the music teacher came out from Bryant, she taught her music lessons in our house.
And we got music lessons free for that, but then it didn't take.
And then we had, well, Dr. Doak, maybe you remember him.
Oh, yes.
The Doaks lived in our upstairs for 13 years.
This is Dr. C.C.
Doak, and he taught what?
He taught biology.
Describe him.
Well, he was just a nice little man.
Where did they come from?
Well, he had just fought in the war, and he came back there, and they both taught all the years, but they lived with us.
Now, she taught in the A&M Consolidated School?
Well, she didn't at first.
She taught out in some of the other places, but she ended up teaching in...
And they were pleasant neighbors?
Well, they lived with us, yes.
Now, when y'all ate, did they cook upstairs?
No, they, well, they did a little bit of it, you know, but they didn't cook meals.
They ate, I think, ate their noon meal out and then they just snacked after that with something upstairs.

those of you who lived on the campus could you eat in sabisa did you all eat in sabisa dining hall much not unless we were invited for something special no did you was mr sabisa still around describe him well he was a very they were there a little little man i think he was cuban wasn't he austrian oh austrian okay but but
But he was there.
Now Mrs. Thompson now, Dr. Bazell's daughter, she told me that he drank a lot.
I think he did.
And chased around a lot.
Well, that I don't know.
They lived up there right across the street from where he was.
Oh, they lived near Sabisa?
Yeah, in the old house up there.
Were there any Sabisa children your age?
Oh, not any of my age.
Oh, okay.
They were grown, I think.
Oh, they were older?
I think they were grown.
Okay.
Let's see, and did y'all ever, you children, did y'all ever play tricks or pranks anywhere on the campus?
Oh, I'm sure we did.
Tried anyway.
Were there any places on the campus that your father told you you were not to go?
No, no.
We would go, you know, in the YMCA they had the confectionery and we'd go up there to get us a drink and things like that.
But there were no other places to go.
Now, tell this machine about the Y.
What happened at the YMCA?
What all was there at the YMCA?
Well,
You got your hair cut.
You went to the beauty parlor in the YMCA.
And in the summertime, we had our swimming class.
And all the kids, Ms. Marsteller, who Dr. Marsteller was on campus,
And she went up there to the Y and supervised our swimming in the afternoons while our mamas took naps.
But that's where we all went and swam every afternoon during the summer.
In that conservative era, what was considered a proper bathing suit for a young lady?
Well, they were long.
One piece.
One piece in my home, yeah.
Were boys and girls allowed to be in the swimming pool at the same time?
Oh, yeah, the kids.
And at the confectionery, what all could we buy?
Oh, I think it was just drinks and ice cream and things like that.
And what other kinds of events occurred at the YMCA?
Well, at Christmas time, we had a big party for the students that couldn't go home and had a big Christmas tree and had a program.
And after 1918, when they had the women's club organized,
They went up on the third floor up there.
That's where they had their meetings.
They had to crawl up there and carry all their food and everything.
How they went up there, I don't know how my mother ever got up there, but she did.
And please describe the Cashins.
Mr. and Mrs. Cashin, they came in the 20s, I think.
What were they?
Describe them.
Well, Mr. Matthews came before them, I think, as the Y director, and then Mr. Cashin, and they were just part of the campus like all the rest of us.
Where did they live?
They lived over by the hospital.
And the hospital was about how big?
It was a good-sized hospital.
About how many rooms?
I have no idea.
Were you ever a patient there?
No, no.
Oh, no.
We weren't patients there.
Dr. Marsh, was he the doctor when you all came?
No, Dr. Ellinger was the first.
Ellinger.
Ellinger, and then Dr. Marsh came later.
Did the Marshes live on the campus?
Yes, right across the street from the hospital.
Describe him.
What did he look like?
Well, he was blondish and slender and a very nice man.
Because I believe both of the Cashin boys have told me that he delivered them.
Yeah, because they lived right there close, right behind Dr. Morrissey's on the little street back there.
If a member of one of the faculty families had gotten sick, could they have gone to the campus hospital?
I don't think so, but they may have been able to treat.
I just don't know.
We had a Brian doctor.
How often did you all go to Brian?
Not very often.
As I say, we were late having a car, not as early as a lot of other people, and by the time you walked down and got on the streetcar and did all those things,
When did y'all get your first car?
Do you remember?
No.
It was a Saxon.
Have you ever heard of a Saxon?
No.
Well, that's what it was.
It was a Saxon.
A Saxon.
I mean, you don't know when in the 20s?
Well, maybe earlier than the 20s.
But anyway, I learned to drive it going to
to church on Sunday, I was allowed to drive it.
And so y'all would go, when your memory begins, did y'all go to Bryant Church every Sunday?
Did you go down there regularly?
Well, we went pretty regularly, yeah.
Now, who else from the campus went to the Presbyterian Church that you remember?
The Andersons, the Cashins?

i don't know whether the andersons and the cashians ever went in brian i just i have no idea when were there some churches organized at northgate do you remember no when they started but it must have been in in the in the 20s all right um you you graduated from high school in 1925 25 i think it was and then went away to college
Where did you go?
Well, I went to Baylor-Belton because Dr. Hardy, who had been president at Mississippi A&M, was then the president.
Well, I was supposed to go to A&M, and at that time they were allowing faculty daughters to go, and they cut me out the summer that I was going to go in the fall.
They cut that out.
What did your family think about that decision?
They didn't tell me, but anyway, I went over to Baylor Belton.
Let's back up just a second.
What did you hear from the other faculty daughters?
What was it like for them to be students at A&M?
Well, see, I was 15 when I went to college, and that's awful young.
It is.
I don't know whether we talked about it or not.
Ethel was in Baylor at Waco, and I was in Baylor at the other one, and Julia across the street was at the University of Texas, and Mary Frapps was at the University of Texas.
How did you get up to Belton?
Well, they took me in the car with lots of tire fixing because we had lots of, you know.
Had a lot of flats?
A lot of flats.
It took a lot of doing.
And your major, what did you major in?
Good times.
And you were there how long?
I was there two years, and then I went to SMU.
for a semester and then I married when I was 18.
Where did you meet this young man that you married?
Oh, I met him as a freshman when he was a freshman and I married him when he was a senior.
At A&M?
Yeah.
How did y'all meet?
Well, he was in the band and we were up on the steps of the YMCA having a student
Was it Yale practice?
Yale practice.
And I met him there as a freshman, and I married him when he was a senior.
We married the beginning of senior week.
What did your family think about your getting married that young?
Well, I guess they lost.
They lost.
Tell me, where did he grow up?
He grew up in Dallas.
In Dallas?
Mm-hmm.
And his major?
Isn't that awful?
I should know.
And where did you all live then right after you got married?
He went to Victoria and took over the Victoria band and taught math in the Victoria High School.
And how long were you all there?
Oh, four or five, several years.
And then where?
Well, then we went to Yoakum.
He took over the Boy Scout for 11 of the 13 counties, and then we had to move to Yoakum.
Well, that didn't last because then the Depression hit, and everything was gone.
There was no money.
So then we went to Cuero, and he taught in the schools in Cuero.
For how long?
Four or five years, and then we went to Bay City.
where he was principal of the high school.
And then they wanted him back in Victoria to take up, they wanted to organize a band and so we went back to Victoria and when he went in the service he was the dean of the Victoria Junior College.
That's in World War II.
Yeah.
And then after the war, when did you come back to College Station?
Well, I came, I lived at home two years while he was in the service in Germany.
And then we went to Germany a little later.
And then you came back.
When did you move back to College Station?
We came from Panama.
Okay.
And so retired here?
Yes.
Okay.
Let's see.
Let's...
How often, back to Belton, how often did you go back and forth?
How often did you come home while you were in college?
Well, as often as I could talk them into it.
And we could take the train.
You had to go to Waco and then come down.
But you could take it.
There was a train that you could take.
And I came home for a lot of the dances.
How much baggage did you carry back and forth?
Oh, I suppose everything we had.
But was that much?
No, it wasn't a lot.
And did you ever make any telephone calls?
Oh, certainly, certainly.
Do you remember when you all got your first telephone on the campus?
Did you all have a phone when you first moved?
I'm sure we did.
Our number was 32.
Students today cannot imagine that era.
Was it a private line or a party line?
Well, it was a party line, I guess, but you called and told the operator who you wanted and the number.
And they would...
But it was very important because that's how we got our groceries.
We had to call them in every day.
Let's go back to this, when you met this special young man.
How did y'all meet?
You said you met at a Yale practice?
Yale, on the steps of the YMCA.
And he was a freshman.
He was a freshman.
And you were still in high school.
Yes.
So I hurried through high school then.
Uh, and did you then go with him?
Where did y'all go on dates?
Well, we were right there.
No, but, I mean, did you go to football games and movies?
Oh, no.
He played in the band, and he played in the, in the Agadam Orchestra, so he never could take me anyplace.
But, and, and the, we got married on a Saturday, and the next Saturday he played for the, the, uh,
file of all the bag in an orchestra did and i had a date that describe the aggie land orchestra do you have any idea of when it was organized where did it
No, but they played, they were earning their way through college is what they were doing and it was very good and they played all over the state of Texas.
That's what I've heard.
They did and it was at Christmas time and on holidays and things they played all over everywhere and Bill played with them after the
The next year, when they needed him, he played with them, giving us some extra money, and because they needed him.
What did he play?
Trombone.
Trombone.
About how many were in the Aggieland Orchestra?
I think about eight, and they were very good.
Whose music did they copy?
I have no idea.
Do you remember any places they went that were kind of exotic or special?
They played in Quero, and they played in Victoria, and then they played in West Texas, and they just played all over everywhere.
Who ran the Aggieland Orchestra?
Who?

i think bozo briar did bozo briar yeah i don't know how that came to me but it did and so did he select the new members well yeah i think you probably probably had to try out because it was a very good orchestra and uh did did he make enough money to pay his a m expenses
Well, it helped.
You know, it helped.
Now, you say he grew up in Dallas and came here and majored in what?
Economics.
Economics, I see.
Who were some of the special people like, let's see, your father was teaching all those years in electrical engineering.
And what was his... By then, yeah, all those years.
He was a dean of engineering by then, I think.
All right, now his nickname I know was Bear Tracks.
What did he think about that nickname?
It didn't bother him a bit.
All right, describe him physically.
He was a big man.
How tall?
I'd say about 5'10".
Did he have big feet?
No.
Big, yeah, but he just, you know, they just called him Bear Tracks.
Where was his office?
In the electrical engineering building most of the time.
Okay.
Until he moved over into the other.
Yeah, and you know, our son Bill, they called him Little Bear Tracks.

uh-huh when he was in school who were some of the the if if i could be talking to your father today reckon who would he say were some of his special colleagues who were some of the special faculty members in the 20s well one of them i want to
Mr. Dillingham who did the, you know, he and Nettie worked together and we had the first TV.
because he built it himself and they did the first broadcast and it was, Daddy was sponsoring Mr. Dillingham and helping him who was in the electrical engineering department.
The first radio broadcast.
Yeah, radio.
All right.
Did your dad have a part in that, was this that first football game?
Well, he just helped him, helped Dillingham get involved
enabled him to do it, but he never did do anything.
And that was in the electrical engineering building where they... Who selected the call letters for the
I have no idea.
Because I understand WTAW supposedly stood for Watch the Aggies Win.
Well, I wouldn't be a bit surprised, but then that was, I think Dutch Dillingham was the first one to broadcast.
Do you remember your dad being excited about that?
Well, you never knew, you know.
Yeah.
When your dad became dean, how often did he have to go to Austin?
Just when they were getting ready to get the appropriations.
And did you and your family, did you all see the directors when the board of directors would come to meet?
Oh, no.
No, you know, there was a building over there.
They had a building for them, and it was on the other side of the Spieser Hall.
Yes, ma'am.
And when they came, they came by train?
I expect they did.
And when the ball games, we'd have at least 12 or 15 special trains, you know, and they all lined up out there.
And Mom and Daddy, every other Thanksgiving, they had at least 40 people for lunch.
And then Mom would always have sandwiches and cake for them after the game before they went back.
Describe going to an Aggie football game.
But it was hot, and you wore your best dress on the first ball game in September and ruined your wonderful wardrobe because you didn't get with one new dress a year.
And it was hot, but you wore it and sat out in the hot sun.
All right.
Did you usually sit with your parents, or were you over in the student section?
I guess I was in the...
I don't know.
I just sat.
My parents didn't go very often.
My mother couldn't.
She just was crippled and couldn't.
Describe the Aggie band in those days.
Oh, it was great, of course.
And, you know, it played for our wedding.
Mama was horrified because thank goodness it wasn't the size it is now.
But they sat in Guyon Hall, they sat behind the stage so it was fine.
But they wanted to play.
Bill had been the soloist for the band for four years and they wanted to do it.
So you were married in Guyon Hall?
I was married in Guyon Hall.
Who was the minister?
Mr. Matthews.
He had been here, and he was a Presbyterian minister, and he came back.
Describe your dress, your wedding dress.
Oh, it was a long white dress, and it was made in Waco.
Do you remember what it cost?
No, no idea.
I didn't have to worry about that then.
And did people come from long distance?
Did you have a lot of out-of-town people?
We had some out-of-town people, but not a lot.
What were the special wedding gifts you remember?
Oh, I don't know.
I've got a whole list.
I wouldn't give a single one of them up even today.
And where did you all go on your wedding trip?
Well, we went to Dallas.
for 24 hours because he had to come back and play for the final ball, and he was taking his final exams in the afternoon of the wedding hoping he'd get through.
Let's see.
During that time, do you remember Aggie Bonfire?
Oh, yes.
Where was it held?
On the drill field?
Yeah, on the drill field.
And what did they burn?
anything that they could pick up.
You had to watch very carefully not to put anything outside you wanted.
And I remember when I was living at home for two years during World War II when Bill was overseas, my father came from the telephone, and he was dying laughing, and I said, well, what happened?
And he said, there was a man crying on the phone.
His truck was on top of the bonfire.
Now, that's a very good item.
That's a very good item.
How did the students carry all of that stuff?
They just managed to do it in the dark because, you know, it was just awful because you never knew what you were going to lose.
Did they steal somebody's outhouse to put on there usually?
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Do you remember anybody getting hurt during Bonfire then?
Not that I know of.
Did they have silver taps in those days?
Yes.
Where was it held?
At the administration.
Just like it is now?
I think so.
Around Sully?
I believe so.
And then Final Review.
That was on the drill field over there.
And Commencement, where was it held?
Do you remember any famous visitors, any celebrities that came to the campus?
Oh, we had a lot.
I came and I think some of the presidents came.

um let's see bonfire oh uh aggie senior rings did do you remember when your husband-to-be got his ring i remember when he got his ring because i got one then they gave you know that was an engagement ring really and i have one it was was it describe it was it a miniature miniature really yeah didn't know that yeah yeah do you
Do you have any idea what it cost?
No.
He couldn't much because he didn't have much.
Did your husband ever lose his Aggie ring?
Yes.
He replaced it and he got one of those new ones that spoiled everything.
The one time he worked in the yard.
He lost it and never found it again.
Never found it again, but he replaced it.
Well, let's see.
I'm trying to think of other things.
All right, let's see.
Did you have younger brothers and sisters?
Two younger brothers.
And they grew up on the campus also.
Yes.
And where did they go to school?
They both went to A&M.
And Frank, my brother under me, got a law degree from the University of Texas after he finished A&M.
Preston was an architect in Houston, Frank.
is a retired, he was General Counsel for Mobile, but he retired a number of years ago.
And it was okay for them to go to the University of Texas?
Well, yes.
After they were Aggies?
Yeah, yeah.
As you look back, what is it about, what is it that builds A&M's spirit?
What makes people so devoted to this school?
It's there, and, you know, in the Army, we've lived all over everywhere, and it's been very special always.
It's just there.
Are there some events that create the spirit?
I don't think so, but, I mean, that's just me.
It's there.
What effect did it have on your life that your family moved to College Station in 1909?
Well, it was my whole life.
It's all on you.
How do you feel about A&M today?
What thoughts do you have?
Well, I'm very proud of it.
It's a nuisance to have so many cars on campus, but then if you don't have a university that grows, you don't have a university.
It had to grow.
If someone were to give you a check for a million dollars and they put one restriction on it,
that you had to give it to Texas A&M, but you could decide what A&M would do with that million dollars, what would you tell them to do with it?
In other words, if you could make a big gift to A&M, what would you want it to go for?
I guess I'd want it to go to the electrical engineering department.
To do what?
Whatever they wanted to do with it.
All right.
I have run out of topics.
Well, that's fine.
We've done well.
Well, we sure have.
We sure have.
And I am very grateful to you.
And we'll get this typed up and get it back to you soon.
Well, I hope it's something you can use.
